    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 38805,
      "SummaryText": "RMP Executive Summary\nPMC Specialties Group, Inc is an organic chemical producer located in the community of St. Bernard, Ohio.  Final products produced include high intensity sweeteners, corrosion inhibitors and specialty chemical intermediates.  Some of these products are used to improve consumer products by enhancing flavor and fragrance.  Others are used to extend the useful life of metals by preventing corrosion such as in automobile cooling systems.  The site utilizes both continuous and batch processing operations.  Raw materials used in the manufacturing of the site's products include organic chemicals, acids, bases and alcohols.  Three of the raw materials (ammonia, chlorine and sulfur dioxide) are reportable under the EPA Risk Management Plan.  Each of these three chemicals are received and stored as liquefied gases.\n\nAccident prevention and emergency response programs for the hazardous materials used on site have been in existence for many years.  The fourteen elements of OSHA's (Occupational Safety and Health Association) Process Safety Management (PSM) standard (29CFR1910.119), established in 1992, have an integral part of our operations since that time.  Equipment is designed, fabricated and installed to meet established industry standards and codes. Hazard analysis studies to identify potential risks, their causes, and to institute safeguards to prevent accidental releases have been completed for all the RMP chemical operations.  These are being evaluated and validated periodically.  Preventive maintenance of the equipment is handled by skilled on site maintenance personnel or approved contractors.  Critical equipment is included in a computerized mandatory maintenance program to assure its mechanical integrity.  Certified process operators are trained in routine, emergency and process safety procedures.  They use automated controls with safety interlocks, leak detection systems, regular inspections and standardized written procedures to monitor the p"
    },
