      "SummaryText": "lant.  Functioning process areas are staffed continuously and overseen by experienced site Supervisors.  Any maintenance repair or operating procedure that deviates from established standards is reviewed, and if deemed acceptable, approved using a management of change procedure prior to implementation.  Work activity with the potential to cause a safety hazard must have special work permits and safety approvals.\n\nTo minimize the impact of an accidental chemical release, processes are equipped with emergency shutdown systems, fail safe equipment, and fire protection.   A majority of these are automatic in nature.  Specialized  chemical sensors are located throughout the site for detecting chlorine, ammonia and sulfur dioxide.  A written facility Emergency Response Plan detailing the responsibilities of the on-site response team has been in place for many years.  Annual emergency response training is conducted on site.  The site has a facility-wide emergency notification system including process alarms, speakers, radios and cellular phones.  Plant Operators are trained as OSHA Emergency First Responders and all production Supervisors are trained as OSHA On-Scene Incident Commanders.  The company maintains specialized equipment for responding to chemical releases and conducts annual emergency drills with the fire department to maintain skills and coordination.  Emergency Response is coordinated with the St. Bernard Fire Department.  If necessary, the public would be notified of an emergency through the St. Bernard Fire and Police Departments using the Hamilton County Emergency Communication System.  Under the EPA Risk Management Program requirements, no ammonia or sulfur dioxide related incident with off-site or on-site impact has occurred during the past five years.  For chlorine, one site employee has required minor medical treatment and no incident with off-site impact has occurred in the past five years.\n\nPMC Specialties Group, Inc is always working to reduce poten"
